export const batch158 = {
  'never-lead-alone-10-shifts-from-leadership-to-teamship.json': {
    base: { id: 'never-lead-alone-10-shifts-from-leadership-to-teamship', title: 'Never Lead Alone', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781605501949 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A good team is what shapes a great leader',
        text: 'The way we think about leadership is changing. Today it is less about one person giving orders and more about helping each teammate lead themselves. Open feedback and shared ownership are slowly replacing the old top down model. Employees are becoming co creators of the work.\n\nKeith Ferrazzi, founder of the research firm Ferrazzi Greenlight, has spent years studying this shift. He shares practical advice on several topics. The first is building teamship. The second is the unwritten agreement between members. The third is turning already talented people into a true super team. The fourth is growing real trust among teammates. The fifth is making collaboration actually produce results. The sixth is drawing introverts into the mix. The seventh is learning to give and take honest feedback.\n\nGreat leaders do not stand above their teams. They stand beside them. Every step a company takes toward a more human culture is a step toward a better workplace. You can choose to be that kind of leader and bring the change closer.\n\nThe future of leadership belongs to everyone, and your next choice could be the spark that starts it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'What teamship really means',
        text: 'For decades, companies put the leader at the center of every success story. Ferrazzi first saw the gap as a student at Harvard Business School, and he made it his focus as soon as he graduated. He joined firms like Deloitte and Starwood and pushed them to value team collaboration, which he calls teamship. He points to two main reasons. First, members lift each other up. Second, collaboration beats top down management.\n\nIn the early 2000s, the Gallup employee engagement survey, known as the Q12 method, focused only on individuals. Ferrazzi went to a Gallup leader and offered a richer way to measure team performance. He calls co elevation the shared promise to chase a common mission while also watching out for each other.\n\nThis matters because avoiding conflict can quietly drain shareholder value and weaken team trust. To co elevate means to speak honestly and treat each other with respect. Ferrazzi says co elevation builds a healthier workplace and saves leaders about thirty percent of their time.\n\nTeamship also streamlines the work itself. Instead of long drawn out meetings, members co create bold ideas. New collaboration tools and AI are reshaping how engineers and teammates work. Peers co lead the work rather than taking orders from the top.\n\nA good first step is to ask where your team stands today. When the team senses untapped potential, it is time to address the hidden conflicts and unspoken criticism. This calls for deliberate bond building, especially for hybrid teams whose members rarely meet in person. Caring for common success means caring for each member too. Stronger bonds build resilience and invite broader co creation. Recognizing one another naturally shifts the culture from leader led praise to peer celebration. This approach supports collaboration and mutual coaching.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Hire stars and make a constellation',
        text: 'Moving from leader led work to team co elevation requires candor and trust. Sergey Young, who helped create the XPRIZE Healthspan competition aimed at extending healthy human life, wanted to focus on other projects while leaving his team self managing. Candor and co elevation cut down on isolated work, encouraged people to speak up, and raised shared accountability. Here is how it worked.\n\nIf a leader hits a ceiling, the team does too. Candor and mutual support form the social contract that holds every team together. You may have heard the phrase "meeting after the meeting," when a few close colleagues talk about the real problems they hesitated to raise out loud. That kind of hidden critique, along with personal grudges, slowly weakens the social contract.\n\nPeople stay quiet for different reasons. The most common is fear of hurting a friend or colleague. Others are simply passive or feel powerless. Yet naming a missed detail can surface blind spots and spark fresh thinking. The challenge is doing it in a way that feels safe.\n\nFerrazzi offers six practices to break the ice. The first is the Power of Three, where you split the meeting into groups of three to dig into nagging issues, then report back and find a common fix. A shared document helps. The second is Stress Testing, where instead of a normal success report, each person gives a one slide summary of struggles and plans for the next phase, and the group works together on solutions. The third is the Candor Break, where the leader pauses the meeting and asks what is not being said that should be. A shared document helps here too. The fourth is Outlier Meetings, where you pick critical growth areas and keep them on the list until the team solves them. The fifth is Yoda in the Room, where a few trusted teammates can stop the meeting with a safe word when they sense a real issue is being avoided. The sixth is Hiring Candor, where you are upfront about the job challenges so the candidate can decide if they are a good fit.\n\nFerrazzi found that small breakout rooms raise candor by about eighty five percent, because people feel less nervous talking in a tight group.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Your business becomes everyone is business',
        text: 'A solid team is made of professionals working toward a shared goal. A great team is made of people who share more than just the work. How well we do our jobs depends on what happens in our lives and how we feel. The same things can also strengthen the team through mutual understanding.\n\nFerrazzi names three kinds of trust. The first is professional trust. The second is structural trust. The third is personal trust.\n\nProfessional trust is simple. People count on each other is competence. Structural trust means teammates can hold different professional views no matter how warm the friendship. Personal trust can transform the team climate. It used to build itself through office life, but hybrid work has changed that. People form fewer chance bonds, so teammates stay loosely connected.\n\nHard feedback goes down easier when it comes from a friend. Ferrazzi remembers a union leader at his first job in a manufacturing plant who walked up to the new manager, praised his work ethic, and then said they should go have a drink. The formula works in two steps. First, recognize the other person is contribution and build professional trust. Then invite them to coffee or lunch to get to know them better.\n\nA quarterly intimacy dinner can warm the room and pull teammates into each other is lives. Sharing a meal builds trust and deepens personal bonds. For everyday bonding, two short activities work well. The first is Sweet and Sour, where the team spends five minutes at the start of a meeting sharing something good and something hard from their life. The second is Personal Professional Check ins, where you ask sincerely what is really going on and whether the person wants to talk. This one is longer and more personal.\n\nIt also helps to skip toxic positivity. Your best today may not be your best tomorrow. Teammates should feel safe to share feelings and struggles. That is the heart of personal trust.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Meetings are not the same as collaboration',
        text: 'Old companies leaned heavily on team leaders as the engine of progress. Today the model is shifting toward employee ideas and joint work.\n\nAsynchronous collaboration pulls employees in by letting them work toward the same goal at different times and places. It leans on shared documents and online tools rather than long meetings that drained remote and office workers alike.\n\nA good rule is to ask if your meeting could have been an email. Asynchronous work answers that by giving everyone a shared document to discuss issues and suggest fixes. People can take their time, share ideas, and develop a few directions to talk through later. It saves time and draws in voices that usually stay quiet, including introverts whose views matter as much as anyone is. Asynchronous collaboration also helps with the team is direction, goals, and challenges, and it clears the calendar of meetings that should never have been there, which Ferrazzi calls calendar bankruptcy.\n\nAnother idea worth knowing is radical adaptability. It encourages crowdsourcing ideas between teams through async work and using generative AI to test bolder team or company moves. For example, AI can build personas to pressure test new marketing ideas, saving the cost of polling real customers. Ferrazzi believes humans and AI will soon be teammates, with AI amplifying our work. Beyond time sucking tasks, AI can handle scheduling and email, which frees people for collaboration and creative thinking.\n\nIn short, async collaboration and radical adaptability strengthen teamship by helping teams work with other teams, breaking complex projects into doable chunks, stress testing ideas with the customer in mind, sorting urgent from important work, and tracking each person is contribution and current focus. AI can sharpen your problem solving if you are ready to share a piece of the decision making.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The power of being seen',
        text: 'AI has earned its place in the workforce, but it cannot replace human connection. Ferrazzi is research shows that more than half of employees leave their jobs because they feel unrecognized. Working without acknowledgment or purpose wears people down. Work is unavoidable, so it helps to value the time and effort we put in.\n\nTeams suffer when their leader burns out. If you lead a team, take a hard look at your self talk and your habits. Carol Clements, chief digital officer at JetBlue, made it her mission to recognize her employees is work and invite them to recognize each other. She asks two questions during onboarding. What motivates you. And how do you want to be recognized.\n\nPraise matters for every teammate, including those who are underperforming, since the right kind of recognition often lifts them up. Every situation is different, but nobody does poor work on purpose. They usually do not see why their work misses the mark. That is why knowing what drives your teammates, or what drives you as a teammate, is so important.\n\nIn a world of global business and global clients, we all need to try seeing life through other people is eyes.\n\nNo matter your role, highlighting each other is wins can lift the room. One method is seeding appreciation, where a leader passes praise to a teammate through friends or even parents, and everyone benefits. Another is the gratitude circle, where after each meeting the team reflects silently and then gives each person a minute or two to share a win or thanks.\n\nFerrazzi also values inclusion and diversity. Teammates feel more at ease when they are accepted, and the team often makes better calls. Pool Knox from Frito Lay shared how the team invented a popular Jalapeño chip flavor by listening to Latin American employees in Texas, who knew their customers is tastes and helped scientists land on a winner.\n\nIf diversity drives profit, why is it still underused.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Turn a colleague into a friend',
        text: 'Where there is diversity, there must also be support and honest feedback. The word candor has been popping up in team talks, so it is worth a closer look.\n\nHonesty always leads to raw insight. What you do with it matters most. Sugarcoating or skipping feedback can make someone think they are doing fine. In reality, they miss chances to grow and risk standing still, dragging the team with them. This applies to senior people as much as to newcomers.\n\nSome who step into leadership assume they do not need peer coaching. But how can they make tough calls without enough feedback. On top of that, many professionals stop developing themselves after a promotion, which dulls their skills and their connection with the team.\n\nJunior and mid level teammates need regular feedback to know where to grow. Have you ever wanted to level up at work but found no time because of your workload. Without steady feedback, the work gets harder, which makes the workload heavier, a cycle that is hard to break.\n\nCandid but encouraging feedback clears many bottlenecks in productivity and motivation. Three practices help. The first is Open 360, a quarterly session where each teammate shares one praise and one growth area for a peer, and the leader makes sure old grudges are not simmering. The second is Dial Up and Dial Down, a self reflection exercise where each person lists what to do more of and what to do less of, then makes a visual reminder like a sticker to stay on track. The third is the 5/5/5 Learning Roadmap, where each person walks through their strengths, weaknesses, and growth plans, spends five minutes updating peers, five minutes answering questions, and five minutes receiving feedback.\n\nNothing beats real friendship, though. Flex CEO Revathi Advaithi believes time together outside the office is vital for teamship. Her way of connecting is simple. She likes to know people as humans, not just as colleagues.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A few things to try',
        text: 'Moving from leadership to teamship is about unlocking the group is collective power through collaboration, trust, and shared responsibility. Every small step you take to build a stronger team brings you closer to a culture where everyone can thrive.\n\nA weekly team huddle works well. Set aside fifteen minutes each week for an open talk where each person shares one challenge and one way the team can help. You can also create a no blame culture by introducing a shared line about mistakes being learning moments, and modeling it yourself when things go wrong. Cross collaboration is another lever, so pair two teammates who rarely work together on a small project to build fresh bonds and new views. Ask for feedback often and try each teamship practice to see what sticks. Rotating leadership roles is also powerful, so let each teammate lead a meeting or a project over the next three months to build confidence and shared accountability.\n\nYour path to true teamship starts now, and taking action together will lift the whole team.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'new-dark-age.json': {
    base: { id: 'new-dark-age', title: 'New Dark Age', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680745344 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Technology is more frightening than it looks',
        text: 'Around the world, technology is tied to the problems we face. It widens the gap between rich and poor, fuels ethnic conflict, and builds a social split that threatens everyone.\n\nWe have to understand how complex technologies work if we want to reverse the trend. That knowledge should not stay locked up among elites and heartless corporations. Otherwise, those groups will keep using the tools in harmful ways.\n\nOur world is becoming a planet of digital addicts, and the shift is so subtle that we often realize how deep we are in only after it is too late. Since this connected world has become part of the physical world, we need to study where it came from and how it runs on purpose.\n\nWe cannot settle for using digital tools without thinking. The fact that your phone reminds you about birthdays does not mean you should skip understanding how it pulls the information. Instead of being grateful for the reminder, ask what is in the code and whether it can do things the manual does not mention. To ask those questions, we need to know the digital language and be specific about what we want to know.\n\nThis literacy is not about every person learning to write code. Someone can code and still miss what the code hides. Writing code is like working on a factory line. You are one piece of a much larger process. Even if you can describe the whole process, you may not know the secret ingredient that makes the product stick in the market.\n\nStaying open to fresh ways of thinking about emerging technology, while keeping a critical eye, is essential to guiding the change. This summary aims to raise awareness about the harm technology can do and to push everyone to ask sharper questions of the people who run the digital age.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Technology is about more than new tools',
        text: 'Most people believe technology has made the world more efficient by cutting difficulty and solving problems in record time. Is that the whole picture. The history of computers shows that power ends up in the hands of fewer people. Take computation as an example. Calculations that once needed several mathematicians now happen at the press of a button. A single person can build a project from start to finish at their desk without hearing another view. That narrow window of experience leaves many blind spots. If others had been in the room, someone might have raised the social or ethical questions that would hold the creator to account.\n\nThere is more. The computing power of these devices lets them process huge piles of data and return results that end up shaping people is behavior. Some things are doable but should not happen, because they damage how we act and the norms we live by.\n\nOver time, systems and cultures have grown alongside apps backed by private money. Take social media. A phone user can download an app, set up an account, and connect with anyone in the world. A young girl in Lesotho can video chat with someone in Australia. As lovely as that sounds, the exchange is barely moderated. Each can shape the other is local life for better or worse. A cultural exchange might pull one person away from the norms at home. They can also trade economic effects through remote work and money transfers. The world celebrates the good and ignores the bad until a crisis hits.\n\nMeanwhile, the app maker can collect data about both sides of the chat and use it however they like, noble or not. None of this happens with the knowledge of the people on the call. They are just happy to be connected.\n\nComputational thinking has won us over by showing its power first, then muddying us with its complexity, and finally settling into our heads as obvious truth, as James Bridle has written.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Climate change can break our connectivity',
        text: 'Rising global temperatures stress data systems that already run hot, weakening wireless signals. The faster, broader, and more image heavy our digital life becomes, the more input and energy it needs, which makes it costlier and more wasteful.\n\nAs the environment shifts, our expectations shift too, and so does our ability to look ahead. Wireless signals lose range and reliability as temperatures climb. Humidity has the same effect. Electromagnetic waves get heavily dampened as humidity in the air increases, and that humidity has been rising. Are we heading toward a time when electromagnetic waves will be hard to transmit. Do we have a backup plan for this new dark age knocking at the door.\n\nTime and space are pushing back against the systems we built to collapse them. Data centers used about three percent of the world is electrical supply in 2015, housing exabytes of digital data. The energy they use has only climbed since, and will keep climbing as data grows.\n\nPhilosopher Timothy Morton has called global warming a hyperobject, meaning it surrounds us but is too vast for any one person to fully grasp. The internet, like nuclear radiation, is also a hyperobject. We cannot fully describe how it changes the fabric of the world.\n\nWhat we do know is that climate change and technology are bound together. Without solid projections, farming, fishing, flood planning, and defenses would be hard to plan for. The damage to ecosystems threatens our ability to make the precise forecasts civilization depends on. We need to turn our attention to these contradictions.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Wealth is rising but spreading unevenly',
        text: 'Money has gone digital. Picture a time when cash traveled on camelback from one place to another. Compare that to moving billions of dollars in minutes through blockchain. Faster exchange rates gave rise to high frequency trading. Stock profits come from the speed at which you can pounce on tiny price gaps across markets. Paired with digital communication, finance built a system that earns money off marginal rate changes in split seconds. One company secretly laid fiber optic cables in 2009 to get information faster than anyone else. The project cost three hundred million dollars, and the company saved about seventy five million for every millisecond it beat its rivals.\n\nThe result is that those who can cut latency without being seen, like private banks and hedge funds, earn more than any single entity should. Some go further and trade in dark pools, which are trading venues hidden from the wider market and lightly regulated by the Securities and Exchange Commission. In a dark pool, traders can move large volumes without drawing attention from regulators or other investors.\n\nHigh frequency trading and dark pools are only one example of how financial markets have become more opaque and uneven. Some players make huge profits in milliseconds, widening the gap between rich and poor. Automation also cuts demand for human labor, so more people lose jobs while the owners of the automated systems take in more profit than they should.\n\nTechnology grows power and understanding, but without rules it pools power and understanding in the hands of a few. As digital tools wipe out whole professions, we need real options for the people they hurt. Policies should require the winners of automation to fund retraining for the people they replace.\n\nIn 1863, telegraphy pioneer Paul Reuter asked that news canisters crossing the Atlantic be dropped into the sea so their contents could be telegraphed before the ships arrived.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Surveillance mixes benefits and worries',
        text: 'There is a constant tug of war between governments and citizens over information. Things are often called classified or a threat to national security by the people in charge, so they keep the details from the public.\n\nWith the new gear that taxpayer money can buy, surveillance has grown to stunning levels in the name of public safety. When the public asks for answers, the CIA and other agencies reply that they can neither confirm nor deny the request. That phrase, called the Glomar response, entered US law and got its name from the mission where it was first used in 1981. Since then, almost every agency has leaned on it. It is a way of refusing to engage, and the default stance of those we are expected to trust, as James Bridle has put it.\n\nSpying on anyone in the world now happens with no real pushback by those in power. You can be tracked through the internet, a phone, a laptop, or any electronic device, and you are likely being tracked. Hackers can take over webcams from afar. What you are reading on your screen is visible to anyone with the means to look. Privacy is gone, and government sits at the center of the game. Each time they are caught, the usual excuse is national security.\n\nThe hard truth is that you can have privacy or security, but not both at the same time. The flood of data available to government is so large it has become a problem. Some covert operations were even dropped because there was too much intel on them to keep them quiet.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Fake news is a problem we created',
        text: 'Content online is copied in many ways. Sometimes a person simply replays what someone else made. Another trick is to take what you find and keep the key terms, so anyone searching for the original lands on your copy. The same idea works on YouTube and Facebook. Creators have used it to drive traffic and build visibility.\n\nThe algorithms that suggest what to watch or read never came with a filter to tell original from copy. Some users were handed celebrity status through verified badges. That move happened because the platforms needed more people using them. The faster a product spreads, the better for the bottom line, so who cares if content gets repeated. Since the algorithms stopped spotting duplicates, it became easy to spin up a parody account to hide shady acts.\n\nToday, anyone can broadcast in the name of a public figure on social media without getting flagged. The brand has been split from the content, which lets misinformation and impersonation thrive. People pushing political propaganda can now buy bots that create posts and comment on existing ones. The mix of humans and bots makes it harder to tell which is which.\n\nThe bots also make money for the platform owners, so those owners only pay lip service to denouncing fake accounts. For them, it is about the bottom line. We are living through a dark time when the systems we built to make communication and learning faster and easier are being hijacked for harm. Specific content is aimed at people to shape their choices. Politicians pay to play with the public is information and decide what to push to stir society in a chosen direction. The same goes for businesses that want a certain group of buyers.'
      },
      {
        title: 'In closing',
        text: 'Over the years, technology has reshaped our society, but we barely understand how it works. We are so deep in it that it tells us how to behave and think. We cannot do much without technology, so we need to understand it and how it shapes our lives.\n\nSo far, our response to the network we have built has been passive. We need to stop showing up underpowered. Cool gadgets that put information at our fingertips do not guarantee a better life. The opposite can be true. We may have so much information that we cannot think clearly about what to do. We need to see the current moment as doing to our minds what the atomic bomb did to people is bodies when it was first built and used.\n\nThe digital age we created is here to stay. We cannot undo what we have made, and we cannot predict what comes next, since we have already crossed the point of no return. We can face reality, speak honestly about what is happening, and act justly in every way we can. We have to put human interest first in everything we do.\n\nEven in the dark, we can choose to build life supporting features into the machines we design. If each person commits to what helps humans, we may find our way back into the light.\n\nA small way to start is to take back control of your phone. Verify the source of any information before you share it. Take social media fasts each week. Stay away from your phone for a few hours, and then for a whole day if you can.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'nexus-a-brief-history-of-information-networks-from-the-stone-age-to-ai.json': {
    base: { id: 'nexus-a-brief-history-of-information-networks-from-the-stone-age-to-ai', title: 'Nexus', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680841409 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A long time ago',
        text: 'In 2024, for the first time in a US election, artificial intelligence may shape voters is choices as much as celebrity endorsements do. That kind of change has a big effect on information and social networks.\n\nKnowing the same story can be enough to build trust between two strangers. As a society, we are hooked on stories. Today, that shows up most in what people post on Instagram, where stories spark emotion and pull people into something bigger than themselves. Maybe you heard that the Bieber family had a baby. If not, you must have worked hard to avoid the news. The whole internet was buzzing, and fans were thrilled, as if they had given birth themselves.\n\nHow many of those fans have met the Biebers in person. Very few. So why do they feel so close to the moment. Because the stories about the couple, including the drama, the wedding, and the pregnancy, touch their fans too. They do not need to have known Justin or Hailey from childhood to feel part of their lives.\n\nOddly, this points back to Christianity. The story of Jesus has tied people together for thousands of years, especially at Christmas and Easter, and it has let them share joy and sorrow together. What other good comes from knowing particular stories. Let is explore that together.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How to build a network',
        text: 'Along with ideas like history, religion, or democracy, information is intersubjective. It is not fully objective, like nature, and not fully subjective, like pain, because it only exists when someone knows or remembers it.\n\nThis ability to believe in something together and set rules is the foundation for building information networks. Modern studies show that repeating a fake memory over and over eventually makes a person accept it as a real memory, as Yuval Noah Harari has noted.\n\nImagine you want to build a network that will bring many people together for the common good. What do you need to know to avoid past mistakes. You need a worthy and selfless reason that will pull people in. Stalinism and Nazism fail this test, because their goal was to raise obedient citizens with no opinions of their own. You also need your own myth or origin story that will inspire people and remind them of the core purpose. The story is fiction and can be updated. Without that, the group can drift into a cult or a dictatorship that shuts out new ideas. And you need rules that help you reach the goal and that do not pull the group away from its values. The Bible has passed a thousand year test for effectiveness, but your rules do not have to be one size fits all. The point is that they make sense for your community.\n\nEverything can be information, but not all information is useful. In 2021, the astrology niche was worth almost thirteen billion dollars. For centuries, the stars have helped match Virgos with Aquarians, guided travelers, and even helped settle political disputes. Newspaper horoscopes and online forecasts do carry information, but whether any of it is useful is still up for debate.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Writing gave us more truth',
        text: 'Many of us know someone who tells the same stories on repeat. Have you noticed that the details shift a little each time, with new bits, new phrases, and even new characters.\n\nThis is not just a modern habit. Across eras, people have changed the stories they tell, either because the original faded or because they wanted to dress it up. Pinning down those changes is hard.\n\nFor example, a mother in a Stone Age tribe tells her children, with sounds, that their father died in a tiger attack. How could anyone check. They could not. They would believe the tiger story, even if it had actually been a bear, since to her the roars were close enough.\n\nThat is why the invention of writing expanded the reach, tracking, storage, and spread of information. Bureaucracy and filing systems came next, since people realized written records had to be sorted and stored. Shared terms, folders, and libraries made finding the right data easier, but they also flattened out unique stories that were hard to classify.\n\nWritten promises or duties feel more serious. We can feel these challenges even today. Interesting things happened with the Talmud. Written knowledge made it easier for Jewish followers to keep the commandments in one place. New questions came up, like how to apply the rules in modern times. One example is the Sabbath rule against all work. Does using a phone or elevator count as work.\n\nPeople realized they needed teachers and authorities to help them handle information, even after it had been sorted. It became easier to lean on rabbis, sages, scientists, and other experts than to argue about what a text meant.\n\nA note worth flagging. Expertise, real or fake, has also caused plenty of trouble in human history. You will see how soon enough.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The pull of the absurd',
        text: 'After writing came the European print revolution, which by 1600 let almost anyone publish anything in large amounts. This should have lifted public knowledge, since information was being copied much faster. But not all information is accurate. With the printing press, the world also spread conspiracy theories and fiction on a much bigger scale. You may know one of them, witchcraft.\n\nIn many communities, there were always people who knew more about nature, healing, and helping others. They were called shamans, healers, or witches, and only in the Middle Ages did such people start to look dangerous. The mystery around witchcraft grew more threatening and built an intersubjective reality. The public did not need proof that witches existed, kept company with the devil, seduced the innocent, and arrived naked to their meetings. Stories from tortured confessions in nearby villages did the job. Common sense was buried under layers of fake news and gossip.\n\nIgnorance feeds blind trust in institutions that can start to misuse their power. The 1487 book Hammer of the Witches, written by the German inquisitor Heinrich Kramer, gained groundless weight. The methods it listed for spotting witches, torturing them, and punishing them became a manual for centuries. Witch hunters could have saved thousands of lives if they had asked why a follower of the Holy Word was so cruel toward a magical claim with no solid proof.\n\nOnce this new reality took hold, its followers, witch hunters, judges, and priests, gained jobs and fortunes, and left written records of their expeditions, trials, and ceremonies to drive Satan out of the accused. By the 17th century, when common sense returned and witch hunting finally faded, scientists were left with a huge pile of baseless documented "crimes" and no clear way to handle them.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The democratic pill',
        text: 'When people say they resolved a conflict with little argument, they often mean a democratic fix. Let is look at how democratic and dictatorial societies have shaped access to information.\n\nBecoming a dictator in the first tribes was nearly impossible. Leaders could try to claim a territory and limit hunting in it, but unhappy members could simply pack up and go berry picking and hunting elsewhere. Tribal leaders also lived in the same conditions and stayed close to their people. Anyone unhappy with their leadership could walk up and talk to them, unlike today, when a meeting might need an official letter or a security check.\n\nA democratic society protects the rights of minorities as well as the majority. Over time, as states rose and fell, the marks of democracies and dictatorships became clearer. They differ in three main ways.\n\nThe first is self correcting mechanisms. Democratic systems can admit mistakes and offer changes. Dictators never make mistakes in their own eyes, and in a crisis they blame certain people or agencies for misreading orders.\n\nThe second is varied sources of information and authorities. A leader or party in power cannot be expert in every area of public life, so they have to listen to media, schools, and courts. In a dictatorship, any other platform with a different view risks exposing the regime is crimes and breaking the people is fear of the leaders. That was true in the USSR and still is in modern Russia.\n\nThe third is room for different groups of citizens. People hold different values and cannot all think alike. As long as they do not endanger others, they should have ways to live by their own plans, even if those plans clash with the leadership. Dictatorships brand anyone who disagrees as an enemy of the people.\n\nLooking at how information has been used for good and bad in these settings helps us understand our own societies, both past and present.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Do you accept cookies',
        text: 'How would you feel knowing someone was watching your every move, twenty four hours a day. What about someone knowing what you feel, think, and dream about, even the parts you cannot share with a partner or a friend.\n\nNow take a close look at your screen. Over the last few years, laptops and phones have become full members of the family. Like every invention, they come with pros and cons.\n\nAny physical action a person takes leaves a data trace, as Yuval Noah Harari has pointed out. Algorithms track what sites people sign up for, what tickets they buy, who they back in Facebook comments, and what they order for the holidays. We also hand over a lot by posting on social media. How often do you like a TikTok video or a reel. How often do you share a post and ask, how do they know this about us. The truth is, we show our cards to the world.\n\nIn modern democracies, careful surveillance, paired with privacy and human rights, can strengthen the system is self correcting features and improve security, like predicting crimes and tracking public health. Dictatorships use the same data to tighten their grip, control people, and sometimes build blackmail files on citizens.\n\nThe digital age wants to keep users online all the time. That has fed the rise of FOMO, the fear of missing out. Now a word on technology, and the main "enemy" of humanity in post apocalyptic movies, artificial intelligence.\n\nIn China in 2023, a facial recognition algorithm helped identify Yuechuan Lei, who had been kidnapped at age three in 2001. Thanks to well tuned code, parents who had searched for over twenty years were finally reunited with their son. A year earlier, Iranian authorities had started using the same kind of algorithm to identify and punish women who wore the hijab the wrong way or appeared in public without one.\n\nWe do not have to slip into technological determinism and complain that we are losing control of our devices. We do need to take responsibility for the purpose of the technology we build and for who benefits from it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'In closing',
        text: 'Today, having information is not a guarantee of success or control over a situation. Even knowing the truth does not open every door. It only lets us see some parts of reality.\n\nSo let is pay closer attention to which information networks we belong to, which regimes we support, and what traces we leave online. A few starting steps can help. Ask your friends where they get their news and information, and check data from different sources to find the closest thing to the truth.\n\nThink about which stories from books, movies, and other people is lives hit you the most. What draws you to them. Could any of them hide a manipulative spin on the facts. And look at the parts of your life that touch artificial intelligence. Learn how those systems work, so you can put them to work for you.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'no-logo.json': {
    base: { id: 'no-logo', title: 'No Logo', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781680948392 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A breakthrough that changed commerce',
        text: 'In the mid 1980s, a powerful new idea took hold in business management. Building and growing a brand could be worth more than making the product itself. This marked a clear break from earlier decades, when production was the main measure of a company is strength.\n\nDuring the Great Depression, for example, Fortune magazine stressed the value of making things and suggested that America is economic pain came from drifting away from production. The editorial argued that the "making of things" was the bedrock of an industrial economy, fueling both income and recovery.\n\nThat philosophy began to fade in the 1980s. Recession hit the world, and even strong manufacturers faced the hard truth that their huge operations, large workforces, and big assets had become a drag rather than an edge. The weight of running large scale production started to look like a liability, not an asset.\n\nThis era also saw the rise of companies like Nike and Microsoft, which took a different path. They claimed that production was a side issue. They used trade rules and labor reforms to move manufacturing to overseas contractors, and they poured energy into branding, the art of building an image for their products in the market.\n\nThe strategy paid off handsomely and kicked off a trend where the less a company owned its own production, the more successful it became. From then on, a corporation is strength was measured by the visibility and recognition of its brand, not by its factories and tools.\n\nMany famous manufacturers no longer make their products. They buy and brand them. The focus is on creative marketing, brand extensions, and fresh imagery, not on factory equipment. When you pick a product, remember that big companies often care more about buzz than quality.\n\nIn this summary, we will look at how this obsession with brand identity has shaped society and how a new wave of anti corporate activism is pushing back.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Brands clever tricks for growth',
        text: 'In our society, we are surrounded by brands. They show up on streets, at sporting events, in schools, and in malls. Our favorite teams and athletes are sponsored by brands, and most of what we see in movies and on TV is a carefully placed branded product.\n\nBrands have drifted so far from their original job, which was to vouch for product quality, that they now exist mainly as emotional selling points. The reason brands loom so large in our culture comes from a special law of advertising gravity. The rule is simple. If you are not shooting upward, you will crash to the ground before you know it. Ad executive David Lubars puts it plainly. Consumers, he says, are like roaches. If you keep spraying them, they get resistant.\n\nSo if consumers are like roaches, then corporations and ad agencies must keep cooking up new mixes of high grade spray. That is what happened in the 1980s, when companies started tailoring their brand image to teenagers. Since brands must keep shifting to stay relevant, they had to invent a "cool" image so teens would spend their money on the products.\n\nAs ads grow more aggressive, we should push back and teach our kids to do the same. Companies would send scouts into high schools to learn what counted as cool and youth oriented, then turn it into ad campaigns. Nike and Tommy Hilfiger were the two big winners of this move, riding the hip hop and Black fashion trend from the start.\n\nIt is no secret that we now live a sponsored life, and with ad spending still rising, we can expect more of these tricks.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Megachains and their contradictions',
        text: 'Despite the talk, market driven globalization has little to do with diversity. Local brands and small shops stand in the way of superbrands trying to take over the market. So what are the main tricks corporations use to push regular shops out, drown out rivals, and take control.\n\nThe first trend, Walmart is go to move, is price wars, where megachains deliberately undersell every competitor. The second, favored by Starbucks, is clustering, where they flood an area with so many chain stores that local cafes cannot survive.\n\nAs of early 2021, Walmart had 10,500 stores across 24 countries, selling a wide range of goods. Over 3,000 of them were Supercenters of around 180,000 square feet, packed with grocery and clothing shops, hair salons, pharmacies, and banks. Of the 10,500 stores, 599 were Sam is Clubs, members only stores that offer big discounts on bulk purchases.\n\nWalmart is recipe for staying the world is biggest retailer by revenue has four steps. Build stores so large they tower over anything nearby. Demand the lowest possible prices from suppliers by promising huge orders. Set your prices so low that smaller stores cannot keep up. And cut costs further by placing hypermarkets next to warehouses.\n\nAll of this helps the megachain build a monopoly and crush local rivals, especially small retailers. Starbucks is method is different. It uses a clustering strategy, opening coffeehouses on nearly every corner of dense urban areas, leaving no room for local cafes. It is an aggressive strategy that "cannibalizes" sales from competitors. The company saturates the market until its own branches start taking customers from each other. Some stores will lose money, but the overall gain is huge. As giants like Starbucks, who can afford to take losses, grow, small businesses slowly disappear.\n\nIn short, clustering and price wars choke diversity and competition, the very values these huge multinationals claim to support. Before you open a business, check whether your field has room for rivals.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The hidden cost of mass production',
        text: 'Nike co founder Phil Knight once said that production is worth little and that breakthroughs and marketing add the value. What Knight is really saying is that to his branded empire, production is nothing more than a dull, marginal chore. Multinationals like Levi is, Reebok, Walmart, and IBM now follow the "Nike Model" and skip production entirely. Rather than make the product, they outsource it.\n\nExploiting people and the environment should not be the price we pay for cheap goods. It is not just factory jobs that move offshore. The old idea that a manufacturer is responsible for its workers goes with them. Global brands prefer to hand the responsibility for production to their contractor. They tell the contractor what to make and how cheap it has to be so the brand can keep pouring money into marketing.\n\nProducts are made in the factory, but brands are made in the mind, as Walter Landor has put it. The focus on branding over making things is undeniably profitable, but someone still has to roll up their sleeves and produce the goods these companies sell under their logos. Usually, multinationals outsource their manufacturing to areas known as free trade zones, or Export Processing Zones.\n\nExport Processing Zones exist in over 70 developing countries, employing more than 30 million workers. Wherever they are, the workers share the same grim story. They are forced to work more than 12 hours a day in miserable conditions. The work is low skill and tedious. The pay is tiny. The factories are run like the military, with abusive supervisors.\n\nMost of these workers are young, vulnerable migrants drawn by the promise of steady work and good perks. The promise is hollow. These low paying jobs can vanish overnight if the big brand using the factory decides to move production elsewhere.\n\nSo rather than lifting developing economies, Export Processing Zones are simply a way for big brands to pad their profits by squeezing workers.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A broken promise of service work',
        text: 'Even though multinationals have outsourced most of their manufacturing, they have not managed to get rid of the "burden" of salespeople. The service sector has become a much bigger source of jobs over the past four decades. The decline in manufacturing has pushed service jobs higher. Over 75 percent of US employment is now in services and retail.\n\nWhen you look for a service job, double check what the employer actually promises. The story corporations push is that retail workers are somehow not real workers, so they do not deserve a living wage, job security, or benefits. Instead of helping their employees grow and support families, companies treat them as students looking for pocket money. The superstore and the mall now host a ballooning subcategory of joke jobs that are part time, unstable, and poorly paid.\n\nThe economy needs stable, well paid positions that adults can build a life on. Instead of full time roles with benefits, many workers are pushed into non contracted, poorly paid part time gigs with no real future.\n\nMost of the big name brands in the service sector pay the legal minimum wage or just a little more, as Naomi Klein has noted. The main reason these corporations find it so hard to pay a living wage, Klein argues, is that they are obsessed with growth and expansion. They built their plans on dominating the market before their rivals do. They want to maximize profit no matter what, even if that means squeezing the workers who are a core part of the brand is image.\n\nThe result is a hollowed out service economy where the people who keep stores open cannot pay their rent, while the brand they serve posts record profits.'
      },
      {
        title: 'How activists hijack an ad campaign',
        text: 'Naomi Klein says a wave of political activism is rising to stand up to big corporations. One of the main tools in this anti corporate movement is culture jamming. Culture jammers parody ads by hijacking billboards and rewriting the message. This group of activists believes that streets are public space, and the best way to fight back against corporations forcing us to look at images we never asked for is to counter the message behind those images.\n\nRidiculing the popular story can be one of the sharpest ways to weaken it. The main argument of jammers has been boosted by the recent rise in aggressive ads in public space. Ads are everywhere, painted and projected on sidewalks, wrapped around entire buildings and buses, placed in schools and basketball courts, and pushed across the internet. At the same time, jammers realized that many media channels sit in the hands of a few corporate giants, so their fight is also a fight for freedom of speech.\n\nWhen culture jammers want to hit a corporation, they hack into its ads and send messages that contradict the original. By doing this, they force the company to fund its own boycott. The brand paid for the billboard, and any time people vandalize a logo, they tap into the huge resources spent to give that logo meaning.\n\nThere is no doubt this move is not enough on its own to break corporate power or soften the impact of branding, but it is a key part of anti corporate activism. The phrase culture jamming comes from radio jamming, which is the act of blocking signals to disrupt the flow of information.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The weak spot of big corporations',
        text: 'It is not just the ads that are under attack. More activists around the world are teaming up to expose brand misconduct. The sole purpose of these new groups is to out the multinationals that benefit from oppressive government policies around the world.\n\nFor example, the Program on Corporations, Law and Democracy studies the history of corporations in the United States and works to weaken their grip. JUSTICE. DO IT NIKE is a group that calls Nike to account for its labor practices. And the Yellow Pages is a covert global network of hackers targeting the digital systems of big brands that separate human rights from trade deals with China.\n\nAccording to Naomi Klein, most of the fights against big brands began in the mid 1990s, a period she calls the Year of the Sweatshop. Back then, a day rarely passed without Americans hearing fresh stories of the exploitative labor behind their favorite brands. A wave of journalism exposed the dependence of big names like Walmart, Nike, and Gap on sweatshop labor in third world countries.\n\nDisney faced a crisis when reports surfaced of a supplier is shocking working conditions, so bad that workers had to feed their infants sugar water. An NBC investigation in December 1996 spread the scandal, using undercover footage to show the near enslavement of workers in Indonesian and Chinese factories.\n\nAll of these events led to the Year of Brand Attack, a period when many superbrands and their celebrity endorsers faced boycotts for their shameful labor practices and blatant disregard for human rights. The public should push corporations to care for both employees and the environment.\n\nIn short, as superbrands keep growing and weaving themselves into our daily lives, they face more scrutiny over their labor practices and international ties. Brand image, the main source of wealth for multinationals, turns out to be their weak spot.'
      },
      {
        title: 'In closing',
        text: 'Logos are everywhere, from the streets to schools and even into our most private spaces. Big brands shape our cultural standards and tastes, and the aggressive marketing of multinationals has changed the old relationship between a producer and its product. Brands have drifted so far from their original job, which was to vouch for product quality, that they now exist mainly as selling points aimed at our emotions and mental space. Instead of selling products, corporations now market their brands.\n\nThe role of manufacturing in our economy has shrunk under this shift from product marketing to brand marketing. Multinationals have stepped away from production entirely and outsource it to offshore contractors. That move has let superbrands drop most of the responsibility that came with making things.\n\nThe brands not products strategy is profitable, but someone has to make the goods that carry these logos. The workers in free trade zones bear the heaviest cost, with long hours, miserable conditions, and very low pay.\n\nThe good news is that new activist groups are rising to challenge corporations. They push multinationals to take responsibility for their labor practices and to be more reasonable about ad placement. Thanks to the internet, people can come together from all over the world to build movements that challenge corporate power and reshape the influence of brands in our lives.\n\nYou can play a part. Check whether your favorite brand follows ethical labor practices. Send the company an email or call its hotline as a customer and share your concerns. Ask specific questions about how it treats its workers and demand fair treatment on their behalf.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'no-time-like-the-future.json': {
    base: { id: 'no-time-like-the-future', title: 'No Time Like the Future', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781681043948 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Surprises push us to search inside',
        text: 'Every person runs into rough patches along the way. The surest way through is to remain ready. Readiness does not invite trouble. It means paying attention and moving carefully. The world is uneven, and even the most vigilant get bruised now and then.\n\nMichael Fox could never have guessed a Parkinson is diagnosis would land on him at twenty nine. His face is his job, so the early tremors created real worry. Even so, he has spent decades balancing the disease with his acting career.\n\nPlenty of sudden turns bring real unease, and we need to remember that. When hardship lands, we have to keep moving, the way Fox did. The path ahead is rarely smooth, and trouble tends to show up without warning. That same unpredictability is what gives life its spark. Holding a hopeful view and welcoming change both matter, because change is often a doorway to growth. For Fox, that doorway was an opening he had not pictured.\n\nKeeping a flexible mind and rolling with whatever shows up is wise. Another habit worth building is quiet, honest self review. Looking inward is vital during a crisis, especially the kind you did not see coming. Solid self knowledge tells you where you are strong and where you stumble. Armed with that picture, you can ride the highs and lows, and the lows are where it counts.\n\nHope is a useful fuel when the plan falls apart. Liking your life also deepens hope, because appreciation feeds a steady mood. A hopeful outlook is a true tool. It keeps you steady when the road narrows. Fox carried that hope through every test, and the tests never broke him. That kind of thinking is the bridge across the hardest stretches.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Earth is brief, spend the days well',
        text: 'Most wisdom traditions land on the same point. Our time here is limited. The recipes for what to do with that fact may vary, but the heart of the message is steady. Fill your days with meaning. The planet only lends us so much time, and any tick of the clock could be the last. Make each tick count.\n\nIt is easy to fixate on a brighter tomorrow and forget to enjoy today. Living is unpredictable and will push you, but it can also be a rich ride if you steer it well. The saying "live life to the fullest" gets tossed around, and people often tie it to fancy cars, pricey dinners, and no work at all. That misses the mark. Living fully means tasting every flavor of life and soaking in the small joys that come with them.\n\nThe road to a satisfying life runs through curiosity, no matter the topic. Want a satisfying life. It is usually free of charge and pays you back in spades. A whole life is one where you chase what calls to you, even if it is that dream role at the office. It is a life where other people is doubts do not fence you in. That does not mean the work vanishes. You can spend such a life doing labor you actually love, the labor you picked.\n\nA reason to live fully has to be found, no matter the wall in front of you. When his diagnosis hit, Fox had a choice. Let the disease name him, or keep exploring undeterred. He picked the second road. His fight with Parkinson is has stretched on for years, and he is still swinging. His grit and hopefulness are remarkable, and many would have stepped away. He did not, because the pull of a full, joyful life outweighed every odd.\n\nTiny pen strokes and a fading sense of smell can be early hints of Parkinson is. Pen strokes that shrink over months or crowd together are a common flag. A fading sense of smell, especially for foods like bananas, dill pickles, and licorice, is another.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Habits of health pay off when illness strikes',
        text: 'Because life is full of wild cards, we need to be ready for any of them. One of those wild cards is a health condition that arrives without warning. Some conditions run in families, but even those give no heads up.\n\nYou cannot always predict a health crisis, but you can build a life that softens the landing. A serious diagnosis blindsided Michael Fox, and luckily he had the foundation to manage it. A diagnosis often feels like a final verdict that shrinks your world and strips the fun from it. You may have to drop some comforts and routines, but the trade is fair if the result is surviving with your life in your hands.\n\nHandling an illness, no matter how heavy, gets easier when you see it as the road back to a normal day. To give yourself a real shot against a sudden condition, you have to build and protect healthy habits so you are ready to make the shifts that ease the symptoms. Some situations may force you to set aside a beloved meal or hobby, which can sting and complicate daily life.\n\nBig lifestyle shifts in the name of managing an illness are hard, but the reward is real. The will and discipline to take on a new routine speed up recovery. These habits are the building blocks of getting back to a healthy baseline. Refusing to adjust your life and habits raises the chance of relapse and tougher symptoms. Steering an illness through its challenges is tiring, and the grind can wear you down. Yet staying the course is more useful than the weight it adds.\n\nThe shifts that come with handling an illness can feel heavy and may require a fresh, healthier way of living. The transition is smoother if you already live a fairly healthy life, because there is less to drop. As Michael J. Fox has joked, he was happy as a clam, but who wants to be a clam.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Loyal family and friends are a real gift',
        text: 'The many twists of life are not meant to be walked through solo. A circle of support is a vital part of surviving and bouncing back from whatever shows up. People crave company, and walking the road alone is brutal.\n\nNo person is an island. Humans are wired for company and connection. A circle of support is a group of people you can lean on and trust to help you stand back up when life knocks you down. It can include friends, family, and medical pros with the know how to help you with whatever is on your plate.\n\nA circle of support exists so you can lean on others when your own legs will not carry you. Family and friends are a trusted kind of support, and it pays to keep those bonds healthy. Given how brutal a crisis can be, every bit of help counts. Fox had the gift of a deeply supportive family and a close group of friends who showed up. They were key in delivering the right mix of hope and help that he needed.\n\nThe person has to stick with the routine that brings full recovery, and it also helps to have people who will help them stay on that routine. Some days bring little motivation or grit to follow a set meal or take a pill on time. That is exactly why we need people around us to watch out for us, especially when we are at our lowest. A healthy network of people and pros can swing open doors if you use it well. Without a solid circle, finding your way through life is a grind. The same network can also serve other purposes, like linking you to openings that change your path.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Aging is built in, so live with it',
        text: 'Life is short and full of hard stretches. That is the truth we live with, ready or not. Healthy living buys us more years, but immortality is still a distant dream. Our mortality is part of us, woven into the fabric of being here. Without an end, some would say, life loses its shape.\n\nFor as long as humans have walked the earth, the story of birth and death has been part of the trip. So what can we do with that ticking clock. We have to live. The answer sounds like a shrug, but plenty of people worry so much about dying that they forget to live. They say life belongs to the living, so we have to do what we can to live fully.\n\nWe should not let the thought of a short run keep us from a full one. We will get older. That is not a thing to fear or dread, but a thing to accept and adjust to. Plenty of people choose to panic and stew over the future and the time they have left. In doing so, they never pause to enjoy the day. Those people often end up with a sour life and little to point to. So instead of letting mortality be a fence, let it be the push to do more with what you have.\n\nLife moves in chapters, and our job is to welcome each one and grow with them. Michael Fox is one of those people who did not treat a diagnosis or a crisis as a fence. He rolled with it and used it as a doorway to sides of himself he had not met. It kicked off an adventure, because life, after all, is an adventure. Life runs against a clock, but the clock should not steal your focus. That focus can slide into a dark mood. The way we frame life and death matters, because that frame is the foundation of the life we build. With gratitude, hope stays steady, as Michael J. Fox has noted.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Hope is a key tool against the end',
        text: 'As we have seen, hope is a quiet but steady thread through this book. For Fox, it was his tool against the heavy pull of his condition. Hope is not a bandage you slap on and peel off the next minute. It is a way of carrying yourself, with an open heart for what comes next. A hopeful person will find a happy beat no matter the weather.\n\nHope is the conviction that things can turn out better, even in the worst hour. By the book, hope is the outlook that there is a silver edge in any picture. The belief is that there is always some good in any moment, no matter how rough. Hopeful people live by this view, and they tend to enjoy happier, steadier lives.\n\nBeing hopeful is not being blind. It is an honest outlook that puts the good in your life ahead of the bad. Hope is not lying to yourself, and it is not about checking out of reality to live in a fantasy. To live with hope, a person has to take an honest look at their life and name the hard parts, and also the bright parts. That honest look is the heart of hope. Without it, the person is stuck in a made up world and may never taste real joy.\n\nThe knack of always spotting the good in things and people is something we all have to sharpen if we want joy. Joy is not the absence of trouble. It does not come from dodging every hard thing. It is the knowing that things can turn out better, and that something better waits at the far end of whatever we face.\n\nFox was able to push through the hard chapters of his life not because he missed how serious they were, but because he could find something good in his situation. His outlook helped him survive and always spot the bright side of whatever he was living through.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A final word',
        text: 'The wildness and randomness of life can nudge our minds toward dark thoughts and feed them. That does not have to be the rule. You are meant to enjoy life, no matter the cards you have been dealt. Michael Fox was handed a Parkinson is diagnosis at a young age, and while that would push some to give up, it gave him a new kind of fuel.\n\nWe take from Fox that life is short and meant to be lived fully, free of fear about what may land. It helps to see life as a doorway to explore who you are and open your mind to a richer ride. But while you choose to live a full and bold life, it is also key to live with movement and healthy habits.\n\nGetting through life is tough, but loving and steady family and friends turn it into a much easier ride. A solid circle of support is healthy and vital for a working life. We cannot do without one. Life is finite, and we have to take that not as a fence but as a push to act. Living fully means doing what lights you up, and it is not about burning yourself out chasing every door that opens.\n\nOne way to live a full life is to be hopeful. Hope hands you a fresh and steady bright view. With that view, getting through life gets a lot easier.\n\nA useful habit is to commit to catching your stream of thoughts, noticing what you are thinking, and then swapping any dark thought for a hopeful one.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
